<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brown'sWife     04-10 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brown's Wife,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adrienne Brown Says She Was Set Up On Drug Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The estranged wife of soul singer James Brown
said Sunday she had been set up on drug charges to pressure her to
drop the assault charges she had filed against Brown after a
beating last week.
   Adrienne Lois Brown said she hopes to reconcile with her
husband, who won a Grammy last year for ``Living in America,'' when
he returns from a South American tour this week. They had already
patched things up somewhat before he left, she said.
   ``I've had a very, very terrible week,'' she said in a telephone
interview from the couple's ranch in Beech Island, S.C., a few
miles across the Savannah River from Augusta, Ga.
   Mrs. Brown, who filed for divorce from her husband after she was
beaten last Monday, was arrested Saturday in the parking lot of
Bush Field airport in Augusta. Police said they had been tipped she
would be receiving a shipment of phencyclidine, a hallucinogen also
called PCP, from New York.
   She was charged with one felony count of possession of PCP and
released on $1,550 cash bond. The same charge was filed against
Ranell T. Wright, 25, of New York, who also posted $1,550 cash bond.
   Mrs. Brown, 38, said a friend of one of her husband's employees
had asked her to pick up Ms. Wright and give her a ride to her
destination in Augusta. She declined to identify the person.
   ``It was a setup,'' she said. ``I was framed because they are
trying to make me drop this case against my husband.''
   Brown, 54, was charged with assault with intent to murder and
aggravated assault and battery after Mrs. Brown was beaten and
shots were fired into her car. He turned himself in to Aiken
County, S.C., authorities and was released Tuesday on $15,000 bond.
   Brown returned to the ranch before he left for his tour late
last week, she said.
   ``We made amends before he left. I did his hair and drove him to
the airport. And he's called every night from Brazil,'' she said.
   ``I did not call the police on him. The neighbors did. But I
can't stop them when guns are being fired,'' she said.
   ``I never wanted a divorce. But what can you do when you're beat
up?'' Mrs. Brown said.
</TEXT>
