<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HitlerPainting     04-10 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hitler Painting,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Puported Hitler Painting Auctioned for $18,442</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil painting said to be the work of
the late Nazi dictator Adolf Hitler was bought at action Saturday
for $18,442 by a Chilean-Venezuelan industrialist who said he
bought it as a gift for his wife.
   Juan Yanez Guzman, 38, outbid four other people at a Santiago
auction to obtain the signed, 15-inch by 19-inch painting entitled
``View of Waidhofen.'' According to auctioneers it was painted by
Hitler in Austria in about 1912.
   Yanez Guzman, a native of Chile and naturalized Venezuelan who
lives in Caracas, said he is not a collector of art nor of Nazi
memorabilia and only bought the painting because he thought his
wife might like it.
   His winning bid was 4.5 million Chilean pesos, equivalent to
$18,442.
   Juan Salinas, owner of the auction house, expressed
disappointment that the bidding did not go higher. ``This type of
thing sells much higher in Europe,'' he said in an interview after
the sale.
   Shortly after the sale, Salinas closed the auction house because
of a telephoned bomb threat. He said the threat might not have been
linked to the painting. ``I've got about three such calls before,''
he said.
   According to Salinas, the painting was bought to Chile by the
daughter of an aide to Hitler when she emigrated from Germany about
1950.
</TEXT>
