<1ST_LINE>u i AM-China 1stLd-Writethru   04-10 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0537,0841</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Li Peng Approved as Head of Government</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4 grafs for 3rd pvs, `Li was ...' to UPDATE with
outgoing president picked to head advisory body</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National People's Congress on Saturday named
as premier Li Peng, a cautious reformer whose foster father held
the post for 27 years, and gave its approval to a program to cut
bureaucracy.
   Li, 59, has been acting premier since November, when Zhao Ziyang
gave up the post to become Communist Party chief.
   On Sunday, members of an advisory body elected outgoing
president Li Xiannian to its largely ceremonial post of chairman.
   Li, 78, succeeds Deng Yingchao, the 84-year-old widow of Premier
Chou En-lai, as head of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference. Other past conference chairmen were Mao Tse-tung, Chou
and senior leader Deng Xiaoping.
   The former president, the only candidate, was elected by 1,839
members attending the final day of the conference's annual session,
held in conjunction with the National People's Congress.
   Li Peng was the only congress candidate for premier, but
delegates were told they could write in their own choice on the
ballots. There were no reports of how many did, if any.
   The premier is responsible for the day-to-day operations of the
government, while the party leader controls the direction of
government policies.
   Li is the adopted son of Chou, one of China's most beloved
Communist officials. A Moscow-educated technocrat, Li has
previously been vice premier and minister of education and industry.
   During the voting, delegates rushed to take pictures of each
other depositing the pink and orange ballots into large ballot
boxes set up throughout the main conference hall.
   One delegate voted against the reorganization of state
ministries and top-level commissions, which was approved by a show
of hands of the 2,877 delegates in the Great Hall of the People.
Two delegates abstained.
   A key part of the reorganization plan _ the merger of China's
railway and communications ministries and national airline _ was
abruptly dropped before the vote. Officials said some delegates had
objected to it, but gave no details.
   The delegates also cast ballots for vice chairmen of the state
Central Military Commission and top judicial posts.
   There was no sign of China's senior leader, the 84-year-old
Deng, who is a delegate and appeared at Friday's session. No
official explanation was given.
   Ninety-two ordinary delegates were also absent.
   The government permitted foreign reporters to watch the voting
from a balcony, but asked them to leave before the results were
announced.
   The congress on Friday elected Gen. Yang Shangkun president and
former Vice Premier Wan Li to head the congress Standing Committee.
   In five months as acting premier, Li Peng has indicated he
favors moving cautiously in introducing market-style economic
reforms. Zhao, in contrast, has emphasized quick implementation.
   In his speech to the congress when its session opened March 25,
Li strongly endorsed the reform goals of Deng and Zhao, but warned
against rushing ``headlong into mass action'' or being ``too
impatient for quick results.''
   In other voting, Zhao was elected vice chairman of the state
Central Military Commission under Deng as chairman. Yang Shangkun
stayed on as permanent vice chairman.
   Zhao has no military experience, and the post is seen as an
opportunity for him to gain the support in the military he will
need if he is to succeed Deng as China's top leader.
   Six members of the military commission also were elected,
including Qin Jiwei, head of the Beijing Military Command who is
expected to be named defense minister.
   Ren Jianxin, vice president of the Supreme People's Court, was
promoted to president, replacing Zheng Tianxiang.
   Liu Fuzhi, 71, a former minister of justice and minister of
public security, was elected the nation's top prosecutor.
   The government reorganization approved Saturday calls for
splitting several existing ministries and combining others,
reducing the total number from 45 to 41. Among the major changes,
the current planning and economic commissions will be merged into a
powerful body directing China's economic and social development
strategies.
   The cancellation of plans to merge the railways and Civil
Aviation Administration of China, the national flag carrier, came
as a suprise not only because of its abruptness but because te
Railways Ministry was regarded as a prime target of reform.
   The train system, China's main means of long-distance travel,
has failed to expand as quickly as demand, and has been criticized
for chronic mismanagement and sloppy operating procedures. Four
fatal train accidents this year, claiming a total of 168 lives,
created a clamor for improved safety measures.
   The congress is expected next week to approve ministerial
appointments and vote on several key laws, including one that would
guarantee business people more freedom from government interference.
   It also is expected to approve a constitutional amendment
legitimizing China's small but growing private sector.
</TEXT>
