<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-88 0044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Zimbabwe     04-10 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zimbabwe,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Party Approves Merger With Main Opposition Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Robert Mugabe's governing
party decided Saturday to merge with former opposition leader
Joshua Nkomo's party in a further move to establish a one-party
socialist state.
   More than 3,000 Zimbabwe African National Union (Patriotic
Front) delegates voted at the one-day congress to approve a unity
accord singed by Nkomo and Mugabe on Dec. 22.
   They agreed to bring both parties under the governing party
banner and create a one-party socialist state in of Africa's few
Western-style democracies.
   ``The entire nation is certainly rejoicing with us today,''
Mugabe said after the vote.
   Members of Nkomo's Zimbabwe African People's Union voted
overwhelmingly April 2 to dissolve the country's oldest political
movement and merge. Nkomo's congress also gave support for a
one-party socialist state.
   Mugabe and other officials of Nkomo's party quit that party in
1963, vowing to begin a violent struggle for black majority rule in
what was the white-governed British colony of Rhodesia.
   Nkomo, 70, and Mugabe, 64, were detained for over a decade
without charge as terrorists. Thousands of their supporters fled
the country to become guerrillas in their two rival armies during
the 7-year-old war that led to independence as black-governed
Zimbabwe on April 18, 1980.
   The two parties had engaged in frequent faction fighting before
the unity agreement.
</TEXT>
