<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Pakistan-Blasts 3rdLd-Writethru a0674 04-10 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Pakistan-Blasts, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0674,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ammunition Depot Explodes In Pakistan; Kills At Least 57, Wounds
768</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE death toll to 57, injuries to
768. ADDS population of area. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `The
initial...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire and explosions ripped through
an ammunition depot Sunday and sent rockets showering into two
Pakistani cities, killing at least 57 people and injuring 768,
officials said.
   The official news agency, APP, said one of the dead was a member
of Parliament, Khaqan Abbasi. It said he was killed when a rocket
hit his car.
   No foreigners were reported among the casualties.
   The Defense Ministry said the explosions started after fire
broke out at the depot between the capital, Islamabad, and the
nearby city of Rawalpindi. About 5 million people live in the two
cities.
   It was not immediately known what caused the fire, and there was
no damage estimate. Casualty figures came from local hospitals.
   The initial blast sent a sheet of flame 500 feet into the air.
Rockets began screaming over Rawalpindi and the western and
southern sections of the capital, where most Pakistani federal
employees live.
   One missile exploded just outside the wall of the U.S. Embassy
compound but there was no damage, witnesses said.
   The explosion of heavy ammunition lasted about 35 minutes,
during which people ran fleeing from office buildings and converged
on schools to find their children. Some rockets struck cars and
buildings.
   Doctors at three area hospitals said many of those admitted had
shrapnel wounds and burns.
   The ammunition depot continued to burn more than five hours
after the initial blast and bush fires roared several miles from
the depot.
   Police were deployed in heavy numbers around the city to direct
traffic away from the blast areas and to protect foreign embassies.
   Craters from the explosions, some still smoldering, could be
seen along the airport road leading south from Islamabad. Defense
Ministry officials said some projectiles crashed six miles from the
depot.
   One unexploded missile lay embedded in the sidewalk by the
children's ward of the National Medical Institute.
   Officials appealed for blood donors, and President Mohammed Zia
ul-Haq said the government would do all it can to help the injured,
APP reported.
   The agency said the president issued a statement from Kuwait,
where he was to attend a meeting of the Organization of Islamic
Conference. The statement expressed sympathy for the victims and
their families.
</TEXT>
