<2ND_LINE>BC-Hijack, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0676,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hijackers Threaten `Slow and Quiet Massacre' Of Hostages If
Demands Not Met</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to cockpit report that passenger being
hurt. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `The engineer...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HASAN MROUE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hijackers of a Kuwaiti jetliner ``started
to hurt'' passengers Sunday after their demands for more fuel and
freedom for pro-Iranian extremists jailed in Kuwait were not met,
according to a message from the cockpit.
   Earlier, the hijackers threatened a ``slow and quiet massacre''
of the hostages, but a noon deadline passed without incident.
   Then, one minute before a second afternoon deadline expired,
someone in the cockpit told the Larnaca Airport control tower,
``They've already started to hurt on the passengers.'' The speaker
was believed to be the flight engineer.
   Two hooded gunmen had ripped the inflatable escape chutes out of
the plane and threw them onto the tarmac, then demanded that
workers remove them from the runway to clear a path for the plane.
   At 3 p.m., the flight engineer told the airport tower: ``The
hijackers are dictating this message. If they don't get a positive
response in one hour and 15 minutes regarding fuel and services,
they will start hurting occupants of the aircraft.''
   The engineer said an unspecified number of passengers were
``sick,'' but when the control tower asked that they be released, a
voice came on the radio and said, ``negative.''
   Earlier, the hijackers said they would force the pilot to take
off and crash into the Kuwaiti royal palace. There were believed to
be 53 people still on board the Kuwait Airways Boeing 747,
including three members of Kuwait's royal family and about six
hijackers.
   The latest threats came after a sixth round of talks between the
gunmen and PLO officials from Cyprus. There was no word on what was
said at the plane.
   During the 6-day-old ordeal, at least one hostage has been
killed _ a 24-year-old Kuwaiti man whose body was tossed onto the
tarmac Saturday. He was shot after authorities refused hijackers'
demands for more fuel.
   Cyprus government spokesman Akis Fantis said Sunday that marks
on the slain passenger's body indicated he was severely beaten
during the 18 to 24 hours before his death.
   In a morning statement, one of the hijackers told the control
tower, ```We hereby re-announce our refueling request due to our
intention to (go to) Kuwait, the concerned country. And if Kuwait
refuses us, a crash landing will take place on the ... prince's
palace.''
   He asked the Cypriot government to accede to his requests,
``preventing the slow and quiet massacre taking place in this
country. We perform (carry out) our sayings very accurately, and we
have been forced to send a sample yesterday.''
   State-run Cyprus radio said the government and the Palestine
Liberation Organization appealed to the gunmen not to carry out
their threat.
   One of the hijackers said they would release the hostages
``immediately'' if the 17 pro-Iranian extremists, convicted in
Kuwait in the 1983 bombings of the U.S. and French embassies there,
were freed. Kuwait has refused the demand.
   Flight 422 landed in Larnaca on Friday. It was commandeered
Tuesday en route to Kuwait from Bangkok with 112 people aboard and
forced to land in Mashhad in northeastern Iran, where 57 people
were released. The jet left Iran and landed in Larnaca after being
refused permission to land in Lebanon and Syria. Another captive
was freed in Larnaca.
   Larnaca airport officials said the airport at San`a in North
Yemen was closed to traffic after unconfirmed reports that the
gunmen wanted to fly there.
   The director of San`a international airport, Mohammed al-Faqeeh,
acknowledged that the facility was closed but said it was because
of bad weather.
   In reply to queries by The Associated Press, al-Faqeeh also
said, ``Anyway our airport is not equipped to receive such a huge
aircraft, and it would crash if it tried to land here.''
</TEXT>
