<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Bridge     04-10 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Bridge,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seto Ohashi Bridge Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Seto Ohashi bridge opened Sunday to rail and
vehicle traffic, linking Japan's four main islands by bridge and
tunnel for the first time.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita called the long-awaited opening
of the 7.86-mile bridge a proud achievement.
   Because support columns for the bridge sit on five small islands
it is difficult to compare the Seto Ohashi with other bridges. The
Guiness Book of records says the longest railway bridge in the
world is Huey P. Long Bridge in Metairie, La. The railroad section
is 4.35 miles long.
   The double-deck bridge straddles a chain of five small islands
in the Inland Sea and extends 5.6 miles over water to link the main
Japanese island of Honshu with Shikoku island to the south.
   The bridge consists of three main suspensions, the longest of
which is the 1,210-yard central span that is 198 yards shorter than
the central span of San Francisco's Golden Gate Bridge.
   Last Tuesday, the Seto Ohashi was made a sister bridge to that
Californian symbol.
   The Seto Ohashi cost $9 billion and took 10 years to build.
   Yasutoshi Kunisue, spokesman of the government-owned
Honshu-Shikoku Bridge Authority, said about 60 trains and 25,000
cars were expected to cross the bridge daily.
   Kunisue said the minimum toll for passenger cars of $44 each way
would enable authorities to recover the cost of the bridge in 30
years.
   Takeshita told about 800 officials at the opening ceremony that
``we can proud of this achievement for future genrations.''
   Honshu was connected with the northernmost main island of
Hokkaido last month when the 34.6-mile Seikan undersea tunnel
opened. Another undersea tunnel has connected Honshu with the
southernmost main island of Kyushu since 1942.
   Kyodo News Service reported that 2,500 people lined up at
Takamatsu Railway Station in Shikoku early Sunday for the first
ride across the span, but only about 900 were able to get on the
train.
   Before the bridge opened Sunday, about 1,000 people each day
used boats to cross between the two islands. The crossing took
about an hour.
</TEXT>
