<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-88 1140EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-LiXiannian     04-10 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Li Xiannian,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China's President To Head Advisory Body</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's outgoing president Li Xiannian on Sunday
was elected chairman of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference, an advisory body that functions much like a council of
elders.
   Li, 78, succeeds Deng Yingchao, the 84-year-old widow of Premier
Chou En-lai. Other former chairmen are Mao Tse-tung, Chou and
current senior leader Deng Xiaoping.
   Li, the only candidate, was elected by the 1,839 members
attending the final day of the body's annual session.
   The conference holds its plenary session parallel with the
National People's Congress, China's legislature. On Friday, the
National People's Congress named Yang Shangkun, 81, a general with
close ties to senior leader Deng, to succeed Li as president.
   Li is believed to be in frail health and, as head of the largely
powerless advisory body, he will be freed from demanding government
duties while being honored for his long years of service.
   Li was less enthusiastic about economic reforms than Deng or
Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang. The appointment of Yang to
replace him is regarded as further aiding Zhao's push to open China
to the West.
   Li has spent more than six decades fighting for the Chinese
revolution.
   As a teen-ager he led a peasant uprising against local
landlords, and in 1927 he joined Mao Tse-tung's Communist forces.
   He was a veteran of the ``Long March,'' the Red Army's 1934-35
epic escape from Nationalist troops, and later commanded 60,000
soldiers as they fought invading Japanese forces.
   After the Communist takeover in 1949, he held posts in his
native Hubei province before being named vice premier and finance
minister in 1954. He remained finance minister for the next 25
years. During the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution he was criticized,
but, unlike most of China's leaders today, escaped being purged or
persecuted.
   He was named China's president in 1983.
   The consultative conference is made up mainly of intellectuals
and members of approved non-Communist parties. Its main function is
to offer advice to the party and the legislature on various
scientific, economic and social issues.
   In a closing speech, Li urged that the conference be given a
larger role in formulating government policies and that people ``in
all walks of life'' be encouraged to air their views frankly.
   He also urged Taiwan's anti-Communist Nationalist government to
take steps toward reuniting the island with mainland China.
   The Nationalists set up a rival government on Taiwan, a province
of China, in 1949 after being defeated by the Communists in a civil
war.
   Taiwan began last year to allow its residents to visit the
mainland for the first time since 1949, but still refuses to
discuss reunification.
   In addition to Li, the consulative conference also elected 28
vice chairmen. Of the 28, 12 are aged 80 or above.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
