<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Lendl-Immigration     04-10 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lendl-Immigration,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Eyes Quick Citizenship for Tennis Star</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of tennis star Ivan Lendl will try
to convince Congress this month to expedite U.S. citizenship for
the native of Czechoslovakia so he can represent his adopted
homeland in the Summer Olympics and other international competition.
   Congressional aides say chances for lifting the mandatory,
five-year waiting period for Lendl are slim despite the tennis
player's personal lobbying effort, including discussions with Vice
President George Bush and Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
   But supporters say a special bill for a 21-year-old,
Canadian-born swimmer now living in Texas, which was pushed through
Congress recently by two Texas Democrats, House Speaker Jim Wright
and Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, opens the door for Lendl, who lives in
Greenwich, Conn.
   Both Kennedy, chairman of the Senate Judiciary immigration
subcommittee, and his House counterpart, Rep. Romano L. Mazzoli,
D-Ky., routinely oppose private bills giving special treatment to
Olympic athletes seeking U.S. citizenship.
   ``If you start down the slippery slope of granting what most
Americans would say is a great right ... and start making it
available on demand, I think you've eroded a terribly important
right and obligation and cherished thing under our law,'' said
Jerry Tinker, a top aide on Kennedy's subcommittee.
   The House subcommittee issued a rule last year warning lawmakers
against filing a plethora of Olympic-tied immigration bills, saying
that the bills are an ``extraordinary remedy'' available only to
aliens with ``extreme hardship.''
   But Rep. Bruce A. Morrison, D-Conn., who has taken up the Lendl
bill following the death of Rep. Stewart B. McKinney, R-Conn., said
the door to athletic exemptions has been opened by legislation for
Tracey McFarlane, a University of Texas swimmer.
   ``I took the position that I would not ask the subcommittee to
break the rule it established,'' said Morrison, a member of the
panel. ``But fair is fair. We've already made an exception on
behalf of someone sponsored by the speaker ... Ivan Lendl's case is
at least as meritorious and ought to receive equal treatment.''
   The McFarlane bill has passed the House and Senate and is
expected to be signed by the president soon, a Bentsen aide said.
Like Lendl, Miss McFarlane has obtained her permanent-resident
status but has not completed the five-year waiting period required
for citizenship.
   After sending letters to the authors of several Olympic-tied
immigration bills earlier this year indicating the measures had no
chance, Mazzoli scheduled a hearing April 20 on the Lendl measure
and ones for several other potential Olympians. Lendl is not
expected to attend the hearing, since, under the panel's rules, he
cannot testify for himself.
   ``If you start doing it for (athletes), why not do it for
artistic ability or for people who are nuclear physicists?'' Tinker
asked. Immigration exemptions, he said, are ``for people who are
literally falling through the cracks; some urgent humanitarian,
family or other compelling reason. If we start doing it for
personal convenience, we'd be swamped.''
   But ``a professional tennis player's playing lifespan is
short,'' countered Kim Elliott, an aide to Sen. Lowell P. Weicker
Jr., R-Conn. ``He said he'd like to wear the U.S. colors while he's
still at the peak instead of the end of his career.'' Tennis will
be an Olympic event for the first time this September in Seoul.
   Morrison argued that the legislation would benefit the United
States more than Lendl.
   ``Ivan Lendl doesn't need this. He's very successful. This isn't
going to change his living circumstances or his tax status or his
income in any way,'' Morrison said. ``While this is a personal
benefit to him, it is actually a greater benefit to the United
States and the promotion of tennis in the Olympics.''
   Lendl, however, is not expected to be at the hearing, said his
attorney, William Bricker of New York. Under subcommittee rules, he
cannot testify on his own behalf.
   Several other private immigration bills are expected to be
discussed at the hearing, including the case of Dan Iuga, coach of
the U.S. Olympic pistol team who defected from Romania and is
living in Colorado, and Jens-Peter Burntd, an East German swimmer
who defected in 1985 and is living in Alabama.
</TEXT>
