<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SnakeConflict     04-10 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Snake Conflict,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rattlesnake Hunters, Environmentalists Square Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hunters estimate that 500,000 Texas diamondback
rattlesnakes were harvested last year, fetching about $50 apiece,
but naturalists say the booming business in rodent-eating snakes is
leading to an environmental bust.
   Rattlesnakes ``are a natural part of the ecology _ it's not like
the communists let them go to terrorize Texans,'' said David
Barker, a Dallas herpetologist, or one who studies reptiles.
``They've been there for a million years.''
   The snakes are in great demand for medical research and
commercial products ranging from exotic trinkets, earrings, belts
and paperweights to $10-per-pound snakeburgers and $40 snakeskin
caps.
   Those cashing in on the snake trade are mainly small-time
operators whose numbers have swelled to several thousand since the
``Urban Cowboy'' craze popularized snakeskin attire in the early
1980s.
   More recently, the oil bust has made snake-hunting an attractive
source of supplemental income _ about $5,000 a year for the most
enterprising.
   ``Cowboys, oil wells and snakes are related to Texas _ that's
what people up north think,'' said George Wills, who calls himself
the ``world's largest manufacturer of rattlesnake products.''
   He employs 28 people at a rattlesnake slaughterhouse in Brady
where diamondbacks are killed in a miniature guillotine, processed
and turned into offbeat products.
   Wills said his best customers are retailers in New York,
Pennsylvania and other Eastern states.
   ``Praise the Lord for Yankees, or we couldn't be in the snake
business,'' he told the Dallas Morning News.
   But naturalists are warning that the business could be a
disaster for the delicate balance of nature.
   A decrease in their number could lead to an explosion of
disease-carrying rodents and rabbits that cost millions of dollars
in crop damage, said Jeffrey Black, a professor of biology at
Oklahoma Baptist University.
   A decline in the rattlesnake population ``could cause a general
collapse of an ecosystem,'' Barker said.
   Bill Ransberger, a Sweetwater snake hunter and handler, has
survived 40 rattlesnake bites. But he says he steers clear of
``those environmentalists.''
   ``You have to be careful with them,'' he said. ``You don't
argue. You just walk away.''
   ``It's hard to get favorable publicity for rattlesnakes,'' said
Jim Seippel, an Austin engineer who serves as chairman of the legal
affairs committee for the Greater San Antonio Herpetological
Society.
   Nonetheless, environmentalists have gone on the offensive. Last
month, 26 Texas animal rights and environmental groups banded
together for the first time to protest a rattlesnake hunt at Taylor.
   Two protesters dramatized their concerns by chaining themselves
to a fence. Police responded by throwing a tarp over the
protesters, who soon unchained themselves and went home.
   The consortium of groups is organizing a nationwide
letter-writing campaign directed at the Texas Parks and Wildlife
Department. The group's goal, Seippel said, is to encourage the
department to regulate the number of snakes killed and outlaw the
practice of pouring gasoline into logs and animal holes to force
snakes out into the open.
   Snake hunters say they are rendering a service _ ridding the
state of the dangerous reptile, educating crowds who gather at the
roundups and promoting safety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880410-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-88 1314EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Reform     04-10 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Reform,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economist Says Local Officials Hostile, Citizens Afraid of Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An outspoken Soviet economist says Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's reform effort is being jeopardized by hostile local
officials and suspicious consumers who fear they'll suffer for any
progress.
   Nikolai Shmelev wrote in the April edition of the literary
journal Novy Mir that key agricultural reforms have completely
failed. He also criticized some of Gorbachev's initiatives.
   He said the Soviet leader's anti-drinking campaign has done
little but make moonshiners rich and that officials are misguided
in trying to restructure the economy and accelerate growth at the
same time.
   Shmelev proposed a deeper reform of farming, an increase in
imported food and consumer goods, and better use of Soviet
financial reserves.
   The criticism in the article and Shmelev's previous scathing
attack on the Soviet economy, published in last June's Novy Mir,
are among the sharpest made publicly by a Soviet economist.
   ``It is impossible not to see that a hidden opposition to
perestroika (restructuring) is growing in the regions from the side
of many local party, government and economic officials,'' Shmelev
said.
   The economist said that while they pay lip service to
Gorbachev's reforms, a ``silent conspiracy'' against him could be
developing or may already have developed among local officials and
bureaucrats in Moscow.
   Gorbachev needs some successes in the near future to show that
his program is working, but his rural opponents have paralyzed the
system, Shmelev charged.
   In rallying support for his reforms, Gorbachev has put pressure
on local and central bureacrats and blamed them for slowing the
progress of his restructuring effort.
   But Gorbachev also has noted that Soviets still have seen little
improvement in the quality or supply of food or consumer goods.
   Shmelev said promises that food prices will go up have
frightened many Soviets into thinking the reforms will hurt them.
He said that fear results from the way government agencies have
operated in the past.
   Officials, who have promised that they will increase benefits
and wages to match price increases, must make an all-out effort to
convince honest workers, the elderly and those with low incomes
that they have nothing to fear from the reforms, he said.
   Shemelev said efforts to open more private garden plots and
allow collective and state farms to sell some of their produce on
the open market have failed because of local bureaucracy and the
central government's own demands for food.
   In his article last year, Shmelev urged that farms be allowed to
decide for themselves how much and what kind of goods they would
grow without any interference of state planning officials.
   He said the ``disastrous'' situation of Soviet agriculture is a
result of the ``unlimited power that administrative layers have
held all these decades over everything that lives in the villages.''
   Shmelev said the effort to combat alcoholism, Gorbachev's first
major initiative upon taking power in 1985, had done little but
send millions of rubles of government income from vodka sales into
the hands of moonshiners. The Soviet Union's serious drinking
problem will not be solved until consumers are offered something
else to buy with their money, he said.
   Gorbachev has called for increasing the quality and quantity of
industrial and food production. But Shmelev said neither has
increased and that planners were unrealistic to expected increased
production while they were trying to restructure the foundations of
the economy.
   Soviet officials have been cutting back on some imported goods
such as coffee and tea but could make a quick improvement in
supplies to consumers by sharply increasing such imports, he said.
   The Soviet Union could pay for such imports and strengthen
itself economically by learning to make better use of credit,
shareholding and foreign loans and by providing better terms for
joint ventures, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
