<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-88 1321EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IMF-WorldBank Bjt   04-10 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IMF-World Bank, Bjt,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Finance Officials to Discuss Cutting Poor Country Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finance officials from 151 nations begin a
week of closed-door sessions Monday, continuing the search for ways
to cut the Third World's trillion-dollar debt.
   The annual sessions at the headquarters of the World Bank and
the International Monetary Fund likely will include discussions of
a number of proposals to deal with the huge debt of the Third World
countries, including one that would create about $29.5 billion in
new money.
   Officials agree that the Third World needs more money to
increase production of goods and provide more jobs so that its
people will have the money to buy the goods and improve their lives.
   But there are many opinions among world bankers and officials
about how the needy countries should get the money: what proportion
should come from government grants, from private investment, from
new loans by commercial banks or other lending institutions, or
from direct or indirect forgiveness of old debts.
   Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III has been pushing a
``menu'' of choices for commercial banks, which are owed about 75
percent of the debt. Growing fear that the loans will never be
fully repaid has spurred the banks to take new tacks.
   The menu includes many items that would reduce the face value of
the debts owed to the banks. One is a ``debt-equity swap'' in which
a bank exchanges the money owed to it and gets shares in the debtor
country's industry. This has been done most extensively in Chile.
   Other proposals are variations of a Mexican plan that swaps old
debt of doubtful value for a smaller amount of new debt backed by
the U.S. Treasury.
   In a confidential memo to World Bank officials and member
countries, bank President Barber Conable suggested more menu items.
One would have banks simply waive part of the interest owed them. A
waiver of 2 percentage points would provide the 17 most heavily
indebted countries with $5.6 billion the first year, he calculated.
   The Institute of International Finance, speaking for 165 banks
in 38 countries, has asked the IMF to create the $29.5 billion in
new money. That would help the debtors keep up with old loans and
borrow more. It is about the same amount that Baker asked from the
World Bank and private banks more than two years ago for 15
countries heavily in debt.
   Third World countries have repeatedly asked the fund to issue
more money in recent years, but the idea has been opposed in the
United States, Japan and West Germany. U.S. officials have said it
would foster inflation.
   One critic, Richard Feinberg, vice president of the Overseas
Development Council, said the banks' suggestion would mostly help
the banks. The council is a private group that studies Third World
issues.
   Conable will present a report to the two institutions' joint
development committee on Friday that says rich countries
increasingly are seeing poorer countries' debt as a threat to their
own growth.
   The more poor nations have to pay on past loans, the less money
they have to buy what the rich nations have to sell, notes the
World Bank president, who is a former Republican congressman from
New York.
   The World Bank and the IMF are owned by the same 151 countries.
The Washington meetings are one of two major gatherings held
annually. The other will be in Berlin at the end of September.
   Representatives of Third World countries will meet among
themselves and with those from industrial countries during the
week. The wealthier countries have their own sessions, with
officials from central banks, like the U.S. Federal Reserve system,
participating.
   The two world financial organizations are led by the United
States and other non-Communist governments. China, Poland, Hungary
and a few others also belong. The Soviet Union is not a member
although there have been reports that Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev would like it to join.
   A session is planned at the U.S. Treasury on Wednesday among
Baker and his counterparts from Japan, West Germany, France,
Britain, Italy and Canada.
   This Group of Seven, known as G-7, has set up about 10
``indicators'' of how their countries work, including such
statistics as inflation and the size of the government's surplus or
deficit compared to the country's total production. The complete
list of indicators has not been made public.
   Baker is trying to get one included that will use the price of
gold, among the prices of other commodities. This is being resisted
by some officials who see it as a step toward return to the gold
standard for currencies.
   The seven will review what has happened in each country with
relation to these indicators, in the hope that the record will give
each some hints on what course future policies should take.
</TEXT>
