<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kuwait-HijackReax     04-10 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kuwait-Hijack Reax,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kuwaiti Cabinet Condemns Hijacking</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cabinet on Sunday condemned the killing of a
hostage on the hijacked Kuwaiti jetliner, and newspapers accused
Iran of backing the hijackers.
   Minister of State for Cabinet Affairs Rashid Abdelaziz al-Rashid
branded the shooting of a 24-year-old Kuwaiti a ``hideous crime,''
the Kuwait News Agency reported.
   He said the Cabinet thanked Cyprus for allowing the plane to
land Friday. After the plane left Iran, the Beirut and Damascus
airports refused to let it land and the the pilot radioed that the
plane was running out fuel.
   The Cabinet also said it appreciated Cypriot efforts to
negotiate for the release of captives aboard the airliner.
   But he said the ministers were firmly determined to uphold ``the
firm principles which Kuwait has always pursued.''
   That was seen as a reiteration of Kuwait's refusal to give in to
the hijackers' demand for the release of 17 terrorists imprisoned
in Kuwait.
   The news agency reported the Cabinet began its regular weekly
meeting Sunday with a reading from the Koran, the Moslem holy book,
``in mourning for the martyrdom of the member of the border guards
force, Mohammed Abdallah Habab Shabib al-Khalidi, who was
assassinated by the criminal hijackers.''
   The independent Al-Anbaa daily said the Iranian government tried
to ``conceal the wave of the wolf ... with a lamb's veil'' by
pretending to negotiate when the plane landed in Iran.
   ``The Iranian rulers ... managed to concoct the play of
negotiations with the hijackers, but in reality they were colluding
with them, and they even masterminded the operation,'' wrote the
paper in its main editorial.
   It was the first outright accusation in Kuwait of Iranian
government involvement in the hijacking of the Kuwait Airways
Boeing 747.
   The hijackers are demanding the release of 17 men jailed in
Kuwait for bombing the U.S. and French embassies there in 1983.
   The plane, which was parked at the airport in Larnaca, Cyprus,
on Sunday, was first hijacked to Iran after it left Bangkok,
Thailand, for Kuwait. Iranian authorities condemned the air piracy
and said they were doing everything to try to end the passengers'
ordeal.
   Kuwait has accused the Iranian government of conspiring with the
Moslem Shiite terrorists who pirated another Kuwaiti jetliner in
December 1984. Two Americans were killed.
   That ordeal ended with the Iranians storming the plane after six
days at Tehran's airport. The fate of the four hijackers has
remained unknown.
   The independent daily Al-Qabas said that ``at least certain
political circles in Iran'' were involved in the latest hijacking.
   Quoting an unidentified Western diplomatic source, Al-Qabas
contended that the aim was to influence the outcome of Friday's
elections in Iran.
   It said the piracy was encouraged by opponents of Parliament
Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani because he ``recently started to show
moderation and pursue policies that differ from those of (Ayatollah
Ruhollah) Khomeini.''
   The editor-in-chief of the right-wing Al-Seyassah, Ahmed
Jarallah, quoted the Kuwaiti crown prince and prime minister, Sheik
Saad al-Abdullah Al-Sabah, as saying the hijackers were mistaken if
they thought the presence of three ruling family members aboard the
plane would lead Kuwait to give in to their demands.
</TEXT>
