<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     04-10 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GASTON TOWNSHIP, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you want to get to this tiny
community in Northampton County from anywhere in North Carolina,
you'll have to fly, take a boat ride or leave the state.
   ``You know the old saying, `You can't get there from here'?''
said resident Shirley Skinner. ``In our case, it's true.''
   The 17 families who live there year-round and 42 seasonal
dwellers are cut off from the rest of the state by Lake Gaston,
which straddles the North Carolina-Virginia line.
   Residents' mail is handled through the Gasburg, Va., post office
and delivered to mailboxes at the state line. ``I have to drive to
Virginia to get my mail,'' said Betty Dupree.
   ``I have a North Carolina driver's license with Gasburg, Va., on
it,'' Edward Bain Whitten told The News and Observer of Raleigh.
``Explain that one when you get stopped.''
   The pavement on the single road in from Virginia ends at the
state line. North Carolina won't touch the remaining one mile of
road, partly because half of it is privately owned.
   ``You should see it when it rains or when it snows,'' Mrs.
Skinner said.
   ``Or when the sun's out,'' Mrs. Dupree added, bringing laughter
from other residents.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WADSWORTH, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lush pastures of Illinois horse
country may seem an unlikely setting for a psychic healer with a
crystal wand, but some of the horsey set swear by her special knack
with their prized thoroughbreds.
   Zandee Zbella _ her first name rhymes with ``hay'' _ combines
conventional massage techniques with unconventional specialties
like Japanese acupressure and psychic readings to treat her equine
clients.
   The psychic horse therapist demonstrated her methods in a recent
session with St. James, a fox-hunting thoroughbred stabled at
Tempel Farms in this northern Illinois town.
   Firmly but gently, she moved her fingertips across the horse's
forehead, rubbing her knuckles along his neck and shoulder.
   ``He can be tense. So we work to get the tension out,'' she said.
   ``It's not the pressure,'' Ms. Zbella said of her technique.
``It's more of a mental communication.''
   St. James' treatment didn't call for the wand, equipped with a
crystal from South America that Ms. Zbella says she uses to attract
and direct positive energies.
   ``Horses are a life force, just like we are,'' she said. ``They
are a mass of energy. In that sense you can treat them using
psychic techniques.''
   ``I'm impressed,'' said Laren Hasler of Lake Forest, who owns
St. James and two other horses. ``She does wonderful things
locating muscle problems and straightening them out.
   ``I don't fully understand what she does. But I have a healthy
respect for it.''
</TEXT>
