<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Nurse-Visas 1stLd-Writethru a0703 04-10 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nurse-Visas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0703,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Immigration Law To Force Foreign Nurses To Leave United
States</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS INS spokesman's last name from Jarvis to Jervis in
5th graf, ``We're simply ....'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of foreign nurses recruited to ease
the U.S. nursing shortage will be forced to return home because
federal immigration officials refuse to extend their temporary
visas, a newspaper reported Sunday.
   The foreign-born nurses were admitted to the United States under
H-1 visas at the request of employers because of the dire need for
their skills, The New York Times reported.
   The Labor Department officially certified the nursing shortage,
the Times said, and the American Nurses Association says about
300,000 nursing jobs are unfilled nationwide, with hospital nursing
vacancies approaching 20 percent.
   But last year, the immigration service ruled that such temporary
work visas would be limited to five years, with a one-year
extension possible, the newspaper said.
   ``We're simply trying to make the actual practice fit the
requirement of the law, which is that these people are here on a
temporary basis and are not supposed to stay indefinitely or become
permanent,'' Verne Jervis, a spokesman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service in Washington, said.
   New York and California will be especially hard hit, the
newspaper reported.
   About 4,000 nurses are affected in the New York metropolitan
area alone, and the first group of five-year visas involving more
than 1,000 nurses statewide expires this year, the newspaper said.
   In California, the number ``has got to be in the ball park with
New York _ maybe higher,'' said Arthur A. Sponseller, vice
president of the Southern California Hospital Council.
   It remains to be seen how strictly immigration officials will
enforce the law. Nurses who fail to leave do not incur any
financial or criminal penalties but they can be deported, the Times
said. But employers face sanctions for having workers who overstay
their visas and who were hired after Nov. 6, 1986, and nurses in
that category are expected to be let go, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
