<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-88 1429EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-DukakisStrength     04-10 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis Strength,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis' Strength: Stronger in New York?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soft support has been the Achilles' heel of Gov.
Michael Dukakis' presidential campaign, but a poll of New York
voters indicates that the commitment of his backers may be
solidifying in the state.
   The development, if confirmed in other polls as the April 19
primary draws near, could improve Dukakis' showing. But that is not
assured: The poll also said Dukakis backers remained less committed
than Jesse Jackson's.
   ``In a low-turnout situation, that favors Jackson because his
supporters are more intensely committed,'' said pollster Lee
Miringoff. ``But the Dukakis support is starting to solidify more.
So it's a mixed situation.''
   The poll by the Marist College Institute for Public Opinion,
released Friday, said Dukakis had the support of 47 percent of
likely Democratic voters in the state, Jackson 31 percent and Sen.
Albert Gore Jr. 6 percent.
   The backing for Dukakis was up 10 points from his standing in
mid-March, while Jackson's was up 3 points.
   As important, Miringoff noted, is that 53 percent of Dukakis'
backers said they supported him strongly, up from 37 percent in
mid-March. Jackson's strong support declined a bit but remained
high, at 67 percent, down from 73.
   ``Clearly there's more intensity among Jackson's people,''
Miringoff said. ``If the more intense voters turn out, that's one
factor that would make this thing get a little closer.''
   While committed voters are more likely to go to the polls, that
factor is not necessarily decisive. In last week's Wisconsin
primary, a CBC News-New York Times exit poll said 45 percent of
Dukakis supporters were strongly for him while as many, 44 percent,
had reservations.
   Jackson's support was much more committed, 60 percent strong to
31 percent with reservations. But it was not sufficient in the high
turnout to counter Dukakis' wider if weaker popularity, and Dukakis
won the race by 20 points.
   Miringoff said the Marist poll indicates that weak support may
be less of a potential problem for Dukakis. ``The process is
further along. There's fewer candidates. The Republican thing is
wrapped up, so the attention is being focused on this race,'' he
said. ``People are picking sides.''
   In earlier races, another important factor has been the large
number of undecided voters selecting their candidate in the final
days. The latest Marist poll, however, found only 6 percent
undecided. The poll had a margin of error of 5 points.
   Miringoff noted that much can change in the New York race. The
new Marist poll was conducted Tuesday and Wednesday, before the
three candidates began campaigning actively in the state.
   A critical factor, the pollster said, is to what extent Gore can
cut into Dukakis' support. Gore's task may be difficult: The poll
said fewer of his supporters were strongly committed _ 40 percent _
and another 27 percent said they might change their minds and vote
for someone else.
   Just 13 percent of Dukakis' supporters said they might change
their minds, and only 7 percent of Jackson's backers said so.
   Still, for Jackson, the slight dip in strong support may mean
that after winning the Michigan caucuses ``he was really peaking
good,'' and has slipped since, Miringoff said. ``The Jackson thing
sort of crested a little bit. That's what we have to watch for,''
he said.
   For Dukakis, he added, ``The direction is good. If he can
maintain that path, he'll be in very good shape.''
</TEXT>
