<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Punjab     04-10 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Punjab,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cross-Border Attack Kills Three In Legislator's Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh extremists crossed into Haryana
state from neighboring Punjab and killed three members of a state
legislator's family, the United News of India reported Sunday.
   In Punjab, Sikh extremists tied three Sikhs to a tree and set
them on fire for using alcohol, the news agency said.
   These and 10 other deaths reported Saturday night and Sunday
raised to more than 690 the number of deaths blamed on Sikh
militants since the start of the year.
   Most of the killings have been in Punjab, which has been torn
since 1982 by Sikh guerrilla activities aimed at creating an
independent Sikh homeland. The victims have included Hindus and
moderate Sikhs opposed to the separatists' activities.
   Rajinder Singh, superintendent of police detectives in Amritsar,
denied weekend reports that the Sikh separatists may have acquired
U.S.-made Stinger missiles.
   He described the reports as ``erroneous, false and baseless.''
   Punjab police officials said Saturday that Sikh militants may
have obtained one or two Stinger anti-aircraft missiles and hidden
them inside the Golden Temple in Amritsar, Sikhism's holiest
shrine. The officials spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The officials theorized that the Stinger missiles may have been
smuggled into India from Pakistan, where they have been shipped to
Afghan rebels fighting Soviet troops in Afghanistan.
   In Haryana on Sunday, state police were put on alert and search
operations were launched for the gunmen who tried to assassinate
state assemblyman Harnam Singh, a member of Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi's Congress Party.
   The attack late Saturday night claimed the lives of Harnam
Singh's son and daughter-in-law, UNI said. Another relative also
was shot to death, the news agency said.
   Harnam Singh, his wife and three other family members were
injured in the attack, UNI reported.
   The last cross-border attack came Jan. 1, when Sikh extremists
slipped into Haryana and seriously injured a legislator of the
opposition Indian People's Party.
   In Gurdaspur District in northern Punjab state, three Sikh men
were tied to a tree, doused with kerosene and set afire on Saturday
night, UNI said. The killings were claimed by the Khalistan
Commando Force, one of a dozen Sikh separatist groups operating in
Punjab.
   Police said the guerrilla group accused one of the victims of
``illicit distillation'' and the other two of drinking. All were
Sikhs.
   The Sikhs traditionally do not drink alcohol, and Sikh militants
in the past have attacked liquor vendors and alcohol still
operators to enforce the alcohol ban.
</TEXT>
