<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ottinger Says He Will Suspend Draft Cuomo Effort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former New York Rep. Richard Ottinger said
Sunday he will suspend his efforts to draft Gov. Mario Cuomo for
the Democratic presidential nomination in deference to the
governor's wishes.
   ``I say suspend because, should it appear that there will be no
convincing front runner at the Democratic convention, I am sure
that all the New York delegates joined by hundreds of other states
across the land will seek to obtain the nomination for Gov.
Cuomo,'' Ottinger said, ``and I shall be among the foremost,
hopefully with the governor's approval.''
   The former congressman, a leader in the draft Cuomo movement,
said he was responding to a letter he received Sunday morning from
the governor.
   On Saturday, Cuomo said ``I've ruled out a draft'' but refused
to clarify the statement.
   Cuomo made his statements on the draft effort as he released the
letter he was sending to Ottinger, asking the Westchester County
lawyer ``not to go forward with your intention to encourage a
draft.''
   Although Ottinger said he will comply with the governor's
wishes, he still will run as an uncommitted delegate in the New
York Democratic primary on April 19. Some of those delegates had
been organized to assist in the draft Cuomo movement.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Rohatyn Calls Koch's Remarks ``Unfortunate''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Felix Rohatyn added his voice Sunday
to those criticizing Mayor Edward I. Koch for saying Jews would be
``crazy'' to vote for Jesse Jackson.
   ``I found it very unfortunate,'' said Rohatyn, chairman of the
city's Municipal Assistance Corp., which was created to bail the
city out of its fiscal crisis in the 1970s. He spoke on the WCBS-TV
program ``Newsmakers.''
   ``I'm a Jew. I lived under the Nazis, so I don't need lessons in
anti-Semitism,'' he added.
   Rohatyn said there are legitimate policy reasons to vote against
Jackson, who is seeking the Democratic presidential nomination. But
he said Koch ``takes away from the validity of whatever his
criticism of Jesse Jackson is by wrapping it into this issue of
religious and racial antagonism.''
   ``I'm not at all sure that Reverend Jackson is an anti-Semite,''
said Rohatyn. ``He may be. But I'm perfectly happy to give him the
benefit of the doubt because he says he isn't.
   ``And I think it's as inappropriate to say that Jews are crazy
to vote for Jackson as to say that blacks would be crazy to vote
for Koch. I don't think that helps anybody.''
   Although Rohatyn said he admired Jackson and had met with him to
discuss economic policies, he believes that ``his economic program
clearly can't deal with the situation that we have.''
</TEXT>
