<HEAD>Kidnap Suspect Leads 21-Car Chase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORTLANDT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shotgun-wielding man abducted a
supermarket clerk, then exchanged gunfire with police during a
two-state, 21-car chase that ended when he jumped into the Hudson
River, authorities said Sunday.
   Police plucked Michael Chamandy, 26, of Riverside, Conn., from
the chilly water and charged him with attempted murder and
second-degree kidnapping.
   ``I've never seen anything like it, except in the movies,'' said
Frank Verdi, who watched the cars speed past a restaurant on Route
121 in Lewisboro. ``It was like the `French Connection,' only in
the country.''
   The incident began Saturday morning when a supermarket manager
in Stamford, Conn., confronted a shoplifting suspect, who pulled a
sawed-off shotgun from beneath his coat, forced a clerk into his
car and sped off.
   The clerk, a 45-year-old Greenwich woman whose name was not
given, jumped from the car unharmed after Chamandy was slightly
injured in an exchange of gunfire in Lewisboro, said Stamford
police Lt. Frank Lagan.
