<1ST_LINE>r i AM-OrthodoxEaster     04-10 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Orthodox Easter,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orthodox Christians Mark Easter with National, Religious Fervor</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orthodox Christians mixed national pride
and religious fervor Sunday in Easter celebrations at this
spiritual center and around the world.
   More than 3,500 Orthodox faithful, mostly Greeks on pilgrimage,
watched Patriarch Dimitrios of Istanbul emerge from church after a
midnight Mass. Dimitrios, religious leader of the world's 200
million Orthodox, carried lighted candles to symbolize the
Christian belief in Christ's resurrection.
   Greek President Christos Sartzetakis toured an air force base
near Athens and said the day ``illustrates an unbreakable bond
between Greece and Orthodoxy and voices our hope and determination
for the rebirth of our race.''
   In Vatican City, Pope John Paul II sent Easter greetings to
Orthodox celebrants and called for eventual unity with Roman
Catholics, who celebrated their Easter a week earlier.
   Eastern Orthodox churches, organized mainly along national
lines, do not recognize the Roman Catholic pope's authority over
their activities.
   The Orthodox church began in the Great Schism of Christendom in
1054, when many churches in the eastern half of the old Roman
Empire spurned supremacy of the bishop in Rome. Istanbul has been
considered the center of Eastern Orthdoxy for hundreds of years,
and believers consider Dimitrios ``a first among equals'' in the
churches' hierarchy.
   The bearded 76-year-old patriarch blessed the Easter crowd at
his Patriarchate church and said, ``I wish to all the faithful
around the world the blessing of the resurrected Christ.''
   Church officials there linked a recent improvement in
Greek-Turkish relations to crowded Easter attendance.
   ``This is the largest gathering we've had in a long time. Last
year, we didn't have anywhere near this number,'' said Orthodox
Bishop Bartholomew of Philadelphia.
   Russian Orthodox believers celebrated Easter in a vigil of
chanting and prayers.
   Patriarch Pimen conducted a service for thousands at Moscow's
Epiphany Cathedral. Worshipers craned their necks to see the ailing
78-year-old patriarch, who was helped to move by two priests.
   In an unusual development, Soviet television filmed the service
and showed a segment on a late-night news program.
   The state-run media and other parts of Soviet society are
dominated by the officially atheist Communist Party. The
government, however, has been paying more attention to religion
this year as the Russian Orthodox Church prepares for the June
celebration of the 1,000th anniversary of Christianity in the
region.
   In Athens, church bells pealed Sunday after midnight Masses, and
thousands of Greek Orthodox faithful carried home the symbolic
lighted candles.
   Political leaders and parliamentarians toured Greek military
bases near the capital, joining in traditional celebrations.
Servicemen in camouflage uniforms roasted lamb on spits, cracked
red-dyed eggs with relatives, and performed folk dances in a
day-long party.
   The celebration mixed national pride with religious tradition,
reflecting the role of Orthodox clergymen in the 1821-1827 fight
for independence from Turkey.
   Adherents of Egypt's Coptic Church watched a television
broadcast of Pope Shenouda III's services. Sunday is a work day in
Egypt, but many banks and private businesses closed to observe the
holiday.
</TEXT>
