<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CommercialsStrike     04-10 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commercials Strike,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tentative Agreement Reached</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative settlement has been reached in a
strike by actors and actresses over pay for commercials that run on
cable television, a union official said.
   Members of the American Federation of Television and Radio
Artists and the Screen Actor's Guild who perform in commercials
went on strike March 21.
   The walkout affected all recorded commercials in English or
Spanish on radio and television. The unions have 100,000 members
nationwide.
   The tentative settlement reached Saturday in New York is subject
to approval by the unions' boards of directors, who will meet in
Los Angeles on Tuesday and Thursday, said Dick Moore, spokesman for
the unions. Actors and actresses will not work until the boards
decide whether to approve it.
   Terms of the tentative pact will not be released unless it is
approved, he said.
   The unions have allowed some commercials to be made during the
strike by advertisers _ including presidential candidates _ who
were willing to meet the unions' demands, Moore said. About 400
companies agreed to make commercials under the interim arrangement,
he said.
   But the strike has forced many commercials to be repeated more
often than they otherwise would have been and has forced the use of
``a lot of old stuff,'' he said.
</TEXT>
