<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaRoucheTrial     04-10 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche Trial,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects ``CIA Defense'' In LaRouche Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge, dealing a major blow to Lyndon
LaRouche, has barred the political extremist's attorneys from
arguing that LaRouche and top aides followed CIA orders in plotting
to obstruct a grand jury investigation.
   In an extensive ruling issued Friday, U.S. District Judge Robert
E. Keeton also restricted the scope of testimony the defense will
be allowed to present regarding alleged FBI harassment and
infiltration of LaRouche groups.
   The judge also denied several requests to dismiss the case,
ruling that defense lawyers failed to show that a prosecutor had
deliberately misled defense lawyers about government infiltration
of LaRouche groups.
   Keeton, however, did find that Assistant U.S. Attorney John
Markham violated an agreement with defense lawyers by not giving
them information about a former LaRouche consultant's dealings with
the FBI. Keeton said he would conduct additional hearings to decide
whether the withholding affected the defense.
   LaRouche, six aides and five of his political groups are on
trial on charges they conspired to obstruct a federal grand jury
investigation into allegations LaRouche's 1984 presidential
campaign raised more than $2 million through credit card and loan
fraud. Four of the organizations are charged with fraud.
   LaRouche, a fringe candidate for the 1988 Democratic
presidential nomination, allegedly ordered three Boston area
fund-raisers suspected of fraud to flee the country. He also
allegedly ordered other supporters to burn incriminating records
and refuse to cooperate with investigators.
   Attempts to stymie the grand jury investigation are detailed in
scores of notebooks seized from LaRouche aides and introduced as
evidence at the trial of Roy Frankhauser. The former LaRouche
security consultant was convicted in December of plotting to
obstruct the investigation. Prosecutors plan to offer the notebooks
as evidence at the current trial.
   Defense lawyers have argued that Frankhauser and others in the
LaRouche organization were working for the CIA and told LaRouche
the agency considered it vital to national security that the
investigation be blocked so that LaRouche would not be indicted.
LaRouche aides then wrote what they believed to be CIA instructions
in their notebooks, the defense attorneys contend.
   Frankhauser and an associate, Forrest Lee Fick, both of Reading,
Pa., are prosecution witnesses expected to be called in the next
month. Defense lawyers had planned to raise the so-called CIA
defense during their testimony.
   Keeton ruled that even if the defense could prove Frankhauser
and Fick worked for the CIA and ordered the alleged obstruction,
defense lawyers could not argue that LaRouche and followers were
protected from prosecution because they were following CIA orders.
   ``The CIA lacked authority to authorize an act of obstruction of
justice,'' Keeton said. ``This defense contention lacks merit as a
matter of law.''
   Keeton also served notice that he would not allow the defense to
present testimony about alleged FBI harassment of LaRouche and his
followers unless it was directly related to the charges in the case.
   Testimony in the trial has been halted for most of the past
month while Keeton considered defense allegations that prosecutors
withheld a variety of documents supporting defense theories that
evidence of the obstruction was fabricated by CIA and FBI
operatives planted in LaRouche organizations.
   The hearings began last month after defense attorneys were given
an FBI document that quoted three intelligence operatives as saying
they had been asked by top FBI and CIA officials to infiltrate
LaRouche organizations.
   LaRouche lawyers sought to have the case dismissed because they
were not given the documents prior to trial. But Keeton ruled
Friday that prosecutors were not required to produce it because the
operatives are not listed as government witnesses. He also said
defense lawyers presented no evidence to counter Markham's
assertion that the men were lying.
</TEXT>
