<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan-FCC     04-10 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-FCC,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Blasts Senate For Holding Up Two Nominations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan called on the Senate on
Sunday to act on two nominations to the Federal Communications
Commission.
   In a speech to the National Association of Broadcasters, Reagan
said that until all five seats on the commission are filled, ``the
FCC can't operate effectively.''
   Reagan nominated Bradley Holmes, chief of the policy and rules
division of the FCC's mass media bureau, last fall to fill one of
the vacancies and in December he nominated Washington lawyer Susan
Wing to fill the other.
   ``Isn't it high time the Senate took action?'' Reagan said in
his speech to about 4,000 broadcasters.
   Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C. and chairman of the Senate Commerce
Committee, opposes the nominations and has not scheduled
confirmation hearings.
   Hollings and other Democrats in Congress have been critical of
the FCC's deregulatory actions, and were particularly incensed when
the agency last August abolished the fairness doctrine, a policy
that required broadcasters to air conflicting views on
controversial issues.
</TEXT>
