<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama     04-10 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pharmacies, Hospitals Short of Medicine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors and pharmacists said Sunday a
lack of dollars caused by U.S. economic sanctions is causing a
shortage of medicines and broad cuts in hospital services.
   An opposition party leader, meanwhile, said the foreign leaders
who asked the Roman Catholic church to mediate Panama's political
crisis should consider organizing an international boycott to oust
the nation's strongman, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   ``By doing the first (asking for the mediation) there is an
implicit responsibility to do the second,'' Ricardo Arias Calderon,
president of the Christian Democrat Party, told journalists late
Saturday.
   Monsignor Marcos Gregorio McGrath, the Catholic archbishop of
Panama City, attempted to bring the government and opposition to
mediation at the urging of several Latin American and European
leaders. But he announced late last week the effort had been
suspended.
   Arias Calderon said he did not favor U.S. military intervention
to oust Noriega but added the general might ``try to provoke an
armed intervention that will let him play the role of nationalist
and military hero.''
   Noriega, as head of the 15,000-member Defense Forces, is the
power behind the civilian government. Last February, a federal
grand jury in Florida indicted Noriega on drug trafficking charges.
The United States imposed economic sanctions against Panama after
Noriega rejected Washington's demands that he resign and leave the
country.
   Problems resulting from the American pressure are mounting.
   Pharmacies and hospitals said they are cutting services, running
short of some medicines and have stopped elective surgery, X-rays
and laboratory tests.
   A pharmacist, who spoke with condition he not be identified,
said he could not reorder medicine because pharmaceutical companies
want to be paid in dollars and the banks are closed.
   He said pharmacists could not get credit and he was out of many
medicines, including some antibiotics and heart drugs.
   Doctors on duty at the Bella Vista Clinic said the staff has
been reduced from 92 to 30 and there were only two aides on duty in
the operating room instead of the usual six.
   State television on Sunday showed the arrival of 800 pounds of
medicine sent by Cuba ``as a move of solidarity with the Panamanian
people.''
   Arias Caldron told reporters, ``What has happened is that an
economy in process of development is regressing to a subsistence
economy.
   ``People are leaving the country and say they are not coming
back. Companies are being forced into bankruptcy. Semesters of
school are being lost, semesters that cannot be recuperated.''
   Panama uses the American dollar as its currency and U.S.
sanctions include freezing Panama's dollar deposits in U.S. banks,
withholding payments to the Panama Canal Commision and, most
recently, prohibiting American companies and citizens from paying
taxes to the Panamanian government.
   The taxes are to be paid instead to an account opened for
deposed President Eric Arturo Delvalle, ousted by the National
Legislature on Feb. 26, the day after he tried to get rid of
Noriega.
   Arias Calderon said the latest U.S. sanctions are within the
framework of the boycott he advocates but said it needs to be
multinational.
   A foreign businessman, who spoke on condition he not be
identifed by either name or country for fear of reprisals, said
commercial activity appears to be 20 percent to 30 percent of
normal.
   Some American businessmen have said they can be fined and jailed
in the United States for paying taxes to the government and be
closed down by the government if they don't.
   ``I think we're going to see a lot of closings,'' of American
companies in Panama, the businessman said.
   A statement broadcast on government television Sunday said, ``We
are paying for the intolerable crime of defending our independence
and wanting to resolve our problems among Panamanians.''
   It referred to ``a blockade against the people who have never
been an enemy of the United States.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
