<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HolocaustConference     04-10 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holocaust Conference,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vigilance Urged Against War Criminals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government officials and legal historians from
around the world gathered Sunday to urge continued international
support for the prosecution of Nazi war criminals and for war
crimes legislation.
   ``There is a continued need to be vigilant,'' said Elizabeth
Holtzman of New York, the Brooklyn district attorney and former
member of Congress who wrote a 1978 amendment barring Nazis from
entering the United States and allowing for their deportation. ``We
can't assume that governments will do the right thing all the
time.''
   Jurists from Australia, Canada, West Germany, France, Israel,
the Netherlands and the United Kingdom joined American officials as
speakers at the third International Conference on Holocaust and
Human Rights Law.
   ``The Waldheim affair, the Demjanjuk trial in Israel and the
Barbie trial in France have all three contributed to a renewed
discussion everywhere in the world and have rekindled the fire of
people's emotions,'' Paul M. Brilman of the war crimes section of
the state attorney's office in the Netherlands wrote in a speech
prepared for the conference.
   Bruce Einhorn, an attorney with the U.S. Justice Department's
Office of Special Investigations, said: ``I don't think people will
ever forget. I think there's a strong sense of doing justice.''
   But he noted that time left to take action on war crimes is
limited because both the perpetrators and the survivors of the
Holocaust are getting old.
   Conference participants said that the sense that time is
dwindling prompted the Canadian and Australian governments to
establish anti-Nazi war crimes investigative units for the first
time last year.
   In Canada, a report on the need for war crimes legislation by
conference participant Jules Deschenes, a judge on the Superior
Court of Quebec, acted as a catalyst for change.
   ``The government just didn't want to do anything for 42 years,''
said David Matas, former chairman of the Canadian Jewish Congress'
Legal Committee on War Crimes. ``But there's a sense of a deadline
that if we don't do something soon, the accused will be dead and
the damage done by the justice system will be irreparable.''
   Robert Greenwood, director of war criminals investigation for
the Australian attorney general, said his country's search for
Nazis ``is still in the early days yet. But it's alleged we have a
number of war criminals.''
   Matas said increased pressure to find and prosecute war
criminals is needed because of a recent ``flare-up of Holocaust
denial.''
   ``It's a form of neo-Nazism,'' said Matas. ``When we ignore the
Holocaust by denying it, we add fuel to the fire of neo-Nazis.''
   The conference was sponsored by the Boston College Law School
Holocaust-Human Rights Research Project and the Anti-Defamation
League of B'nai B'rith-Rena Herstein of Warsaw Memorial Fund.
</TEXT>
