<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Kirk-Democrats     04-10 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kirk-Democrats,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kirk Says Tight Race Will Help Democrats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The close fight for the Democratic presidential
nomination will help the party in the general election while Vice
President George Bush is starved for media attention, Democratic
Party chief Paul Kirk said Sunday.
   Democratic National Committee Chairman Kirk said the battle
between Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, Jesse Jackson and
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore is the party's strength, not its
weakness.
   On the Republican side, Kirk said, Bush has had little media
exposure since early March, when his near-sweep on Super Tuesday
all but wrapped up the nomination for him.
   ``I missed the Republican debate about pedigree, family fortunes
and blind trusts,'' Kirk said as he attended a $500-per-plate
luncheon to raise funds for the final election this fall.
   Earlier in the GOP campaign, Sen. Bob Dole needled Bush for his
silver-spoon background and the Bush campaign raised questions
about the handling of Dole's wife Elizabeth's blind trust.
   ``It was not really a debate about the future of our country,''
Kirk said.
   Many Democrats have expressed concern that a protracted
nomination fight would allow Bush to gather strength while the
Democrats attack one another.
   But Kirk said, ``Every one of these candidates has said
privately and publicly that if they don't get the nomination,
they'll be supportive of whoever is.''
   Dukakis has a slight lead over Jackson in the latest AP delegate
count, 745 to 708. Kirk said it was unlikely any candidate would
emerge at the end of the primary season with the 2,082 delegates
necessary to clinch the nomination.
   But he said there would likely be a winner on the first ballot
at the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta.
   ``A mathematical majority may not come until the roll is
called,'' Kirk said. Selecting a nominee without any destructive
infighting at the convention is crucial to victory in November, he
said.
   ``We have the opportunity to go to a convention and demonstrate
that by conducting our own business properly, this party is ready
to go on and lead the country,'' he said, ``as long as everyone is
treated fairly and everyone plays by the rules and doesn't try to
change the rules in the ninth inning.''
   The latter portion of his remark apparently referred to Jesse
Jackson's vocal dissatisfaction with party rules in 1984.
   Sunday's fund-raiser was slated to raise more than $250,000 for
the party's presidential ``victory fund.'' The party has raised $3
million to date this year toward a goal of more than $8 million,
the federal limit for a national committee to spend toward the
final election.
   Party spokeswoman Julie Anbender said the party is already ahead
of its 1984 fund-raising performance of $2.3 million.
</TEXT>
