<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IslamicSummit     04-10 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Islamic Summit,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslem States Offer Support For Kuwait In Hijack Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of other Moslem states offered support
Sunday for Kuwait in its hijack crisis as a two-day meeting of
Islamic leaders opened.
   ``We unequivocally condemn this outrage,'' said Sharifuddin Pir
Zadeh, a Pakistani who is secretary-general of the 46-nation
Organization of Islamic Conference.
   ``In this hour of deep distress, we express full solidarity with
Kuwait and for its principled stand in refusing to yield to
blackmail and pressure of hijackers,'' he said.
   The hijackers are threatening to kill passengers on the Kuwait
Airways Boeing 747 unless the Kuwaiti government releases 17
pro-Iranian terrorists convicted of bombings in Kuwait in 1983.
   At least six gunmen commandeered the jumbo jet Tuesday while it
was en route from Thailand to Kuwait. The pilot was forced to land
first in Mashhad, Iran, and then flew the jetliner to Larnaca,
Cyprus, Friday.
   The Islamic gathering was attended by the leaders of seven
Moslem nations other than Kuwait, including Pakistani President
Mohammed Zia ul-Haq and Palestine Liberation Organization chairman
Yasser Arafat.
   But Zia announced he would return home immediately after
explosions Sunday at an ammunition dump on the outskirts of
Islamabad killed more than 70 people and injurd at least 800.
   Arafat, who arrived from Moscow, told reporters the PLO was
``doing our best for our brothers the Kuwaitis'' in trying to
mediate an end to the 6-day-old hijack standoff.
   Before leaving, Zia told the conference chairman, Sheik Jaber
al-Ahmed al-Sabah, the Kuwaiti emir, that Pakistan's people were
with the Kuwaitis in ``your hour of difficulty.
   ``We hope that the tragedy of the victims of this incident of
international terrorism will soon be relieved,'' he said.
   The meeting is to report on implementation of decisions made at
the 1987 Islamic summit concerning the Iran-Iraq war, the
Palestinian-Israeli conflict and the war in Afghanistan. The 1987
summit was hosted by Kuwait, and the emir is the chairman of the
conference through 1989.
   Others attending were Presidents Kenan Evren of Turkey and
Maumoun Abdul-Gayoum of the Maldives, Prime Minister Ezzeldin
al-Laraki of Morocco and Foreign Ministers Mukhtar Bong of Gabon
and Ibrahim Faal of Senegal.
   The Kuwaiti emir deplored the escalation in the Iran-Iraq war
and appealed to Iran to respond to peace efforts whether they are
carried out by the United Nations or the Organization of Islamic
Conference. Both warring parties are members of the conference.
   Although Iran refused to receive an Islamic delegation the 1987
summit had tried to send to Tehran, ``our hope in the future
exceeds our regret in the past,'' the sheik said. Iran and Iraq
have been at war since September 1980.
   The Kuwaiti ruler praised the Palestinian uprising in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip as ``the sound of right
which has crashed through the sound barrier that the Israeli entity
is trying to impose on the Palestine question.''
   He added: ``The uprising reflects the Palestinian people's
determination to regain their inalienable rights, including the
right to self-determination and the setting up an of an independent
state under PLO leadership.''
</TEXT>
