<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PennState-Blacks     04-10 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Penn State-Blacks,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Students Meet At Local Church In Wake Of Sit-In Arrests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black students at Penn State
University who were arrested after a 15-hour sit-in gathered at a
local church Sunday, and said they still hope to meet with the
university president.
   ``As long as we have one voice and stay consistent, we can
pretty much have the university do what they say they want to do,''
Robert Blair, a student leader, told a group of 100 protesters and
supporters.
   Blair and other student leaders have said Penn State has failed
to live up to promises to adequately increase black enrollment and
faculty, and give blacks equal opportunity.
   Last fall, Penn State failed to reach a court-mandated goal of 5
percent minority enrollment. Penn State has 2,424 blacks, or 3.6
percent of its student body of about 67,000.
   ``We addressed the same problems 20 years ago as we do today. We
don't want to have to address the problems in the '90s,'' said
Robert E. Ross, an alumnus who is an officer with Division 851 of
the Brotherhood of Locomotive Engineers in Philadelphia.
   Ross said he had been contacting fellow alumni to try to get
support and possibly legal representatation for the students.
   Students who had occupied a university building and their
supporters gathered to map strategy before a service at the United
Black Fellowship Community Church, a half-mile from the campus.
   Student leaders said they still wanted to meet with university
President Bryce Jordan and senior administrators to discuss
minority concerns.
   More than 150 students, most of them black, began their
occupation of the university's telecommunications building Friday
afternoon when Jordan did not show up for a scheduled meeting with
black student leaders.
   Police ended the sit-in Saturday morning by arresting 91
students for trespassing or disorderly conduct. Other students
participating had already left.
   Jordan, in a statement issued Saturday night, said a meeting
remained possible with the black student leaders.
   ``We wish to discuss their concerns under mutually agreeable
conditions so that the university's affirmative action program can
move forward with the support of the entire Penn State community,''
Jordan said.
   Bill Mahon, a Penn State spokesman, said Jordan and other top
administrators didn't attend Friday's meeting because the
administration couldn't reach student leaders to discuss the
meeting's ground rules.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
