<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-88 1926EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UAW-Chrysler     04-10 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UAW-Chrysler,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bargainers Says Chrysler Workers Earned Job Security Assurances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union bargainers preparing to represent Chrysler
Corp. employees at national contract negotiations say they will be
demanding job protections that workers earned through years of
sacrifices.
   United Auto Workers Vice President Marc Stepp, who took charge
of the union's Chrysler department in 1977, first led national
negotiations with the automaker in 1979. This year's talks,
covering 59,500 active and 8,000 laid-off workers, will be his last.
   Before he retires, Stepp said, he wants to finish bringing
Chrysler workers back on par with their counterparts at the top two
automakers, General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co.
   The UAW signed contracts with Ford and GM last fall that forbade
layoffs for any reason except slow sales. Job security is just as
big an issue at Chrysler, which has pushed constantly to
``outsource,'' or move work to lower-cost outside suppliers.
   The bargainers say they need protection from moves such as
Chrysler's recent attempt to sell its 28,000-worker Acustar Inc.
parts subsidiary. That plan, which Chrysler backed down from last
month, caused such bitterness that labor and management decided to
start negotiations early instead of waiting to begin talks in
mid-July. Chrysler's contract expires Sept. 14.
   Chrysler Vice President Anthony St. John has acknowledged that
Chrysler will work within the pattern established with Ford and GM.
He has said that Chrysler wants to reach an early settlement to end
the strife with its workers.
   Part of Stepp's goal in this year's talks is a two-year
contract, so that all Big Three contracts will expire together in
1990 for the first time since 1979.
   That year, the union's Chrysler council and all local UAW
officials _ about 1,400 delegates _ met in Kansas City, Mo., and
approved deep sacrifices to save the ailing No. 3 automaker.
   The UAW eventually gave nearly $2 billion in concessions while
helping win support in Congress for $1.2 billion in federal loan
guarantees to rescue Chrysler, which began operating in the black
again in 1982.
   More than 140 Chrysler council delegates returned to Kansas City
last week for a strategy session before returning to the table
April 18.
   Stepp instructed bargainers not to speak to reporters, and those
delegates who would talk refused to be quoted by name. But almost
with one voice, they insisted that workers shared the credit with
Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca for turning the company around.
   ``We were a family, a team. Lee Iacocca was just a guy who'd
been fired by Ford,'' said one delegate.
   In a debate over whether to include about 1,000 former American
Motors Corp. UAW workers from Kenosha, Wis., under the Chrysler
contract, several opponents used the same argument: that they
didn't live through the cuts.
   The Kenosha workers eventually were admitted last week, but with
limits on how their seniority would transfer into other Chrysler
plants. Chrysler bought AMC last August, leaving 1,000 workers at
two Kenosha installations to either bargain with Chrysler on their
own or come under the national contract.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
