<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hijack-Airport     04-10 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijack-Airport,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hijack Drama Grips Cyprus Airport</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL ALEXANDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many Cypriot families spent the Greek
Orthodox Easter watching events in the Kuwaiti airliner hijack
drama at Larnaca's beachside airport, which continued to operate.
   More than a dozen cars and motorbikes lined a road beside the
airport. People sat atop sandy knolls nearby to watch the
blue-and-white Kuwait Airways jumbo jet through binoculars.
   With the airport functioning normally, tension was not evident.
   Police officers, armed with automatic rifles, stayed well away
from the plane.
   Few people were allowed to approach the Boeing 747, which was
hijacked Tuesday on a flight from Thailand to Kuwait by at least
six gunmen. Portable generators used to power air conditioning and
lights occasionally were changed as they ran out of fuel on the
tarmac beneath the plane.
   Food and supplies were pulled up by rope. After breakfast was
provided Saturday, the hijackers said passengers were asking for
cigarettes.
   The hijackers obviously were well informed about the plane. When
told that the food was still frozen, they said they already had
turned on the microwave ovens.
   And when a spare air conditioner was taken aboard they said they
didn't need instructions on how to install it.
   At one point, two hijackers, wearing blue hoods, appeared in the
plane's doorway and threw a huge bag onto the tarmac.
   It contained the emergency chutes that had been ripped out to
block any possible escape attempt by the passengers.
   ``What about the chutes you threw out of the aircraft?'' the
control tower asked by radio.
   ``Well, take it away. It belongs to Kuwait Airways,'' the
hijacker who has served as the plane's spokesman replied in broken
English.
   There was a request from the plane for the times of sunrise and
sunset in Cyprus, indicating the Moslem hijackers wanted to know
the proper time to kneel and pray facing the holy city of Mecca in
Saudi Arabia.
   For other sections of the small airport, which has only four
departure gates, it was business as usual as the summer tourist
business began to slowly increase.
   Airliners flew in and out past the Kuwaiti jetliner parked at
the end of a runway beside the Mediterranean.
   Journalists set up shop in a second-floor conference room. They
were silent when a radio monitor, set to the frequency of
communications between the plane and the control tower, began
broadcasting..
   Conversations between negotiators and hijackers were
surprisingly polite and calm, even when the gunmen said they had
killed a passengers and a coffin was needed.
   But the hijackers warned officials against stalling when they
were told that no one could be found to refuel the jet because of
the holiday. Other planes were taking on fuel within sight of the
hijackers.
</TEXT>
