<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0727,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Sees Soviet Troop Withdrawal As Aid to Better East-West
Relations</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: To update with Reagan returning to Washington, subs 12th graf
pvs: Reagan stopped ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Sunday the expected
withdrawal of Soviet troops from Afghanistan was ``a major
contribution'' to improving East-West relations and pledged
continued U.S. military aid to the Afghan rebels.
   Differences over U.S. and Soviet aid to rival factions in
Afghanistan had been a major obstacle to negotiations in Geneva on
a settlement of the eight-year war and the withdrawal of an
estimated 115,000 Soviet troops.
   However, the two sides appear to have agreed on a compromise
under which the Soviets will continue providing aid to the Marxist
government while the United States gives assistance to the
anti-communist insurgents.
   Reagan, in a speech to the annual convention of the National
Association of Broadcasters at a downtown hotel, said he
anticipated an agreement would be signed in Geneva ``in the very
near future'' for a Soviet withdrawal.
   The pact, negotiated under the auspices of the United Nations,
is expected to be signed this week, with the Soviet Union and the
United States guaranteeing a settlement of the war.
   ``If that accord is complied with, and the Soviets withdraw
irrevocably from that long-suffering country, this will be a great
victory for its heroic people, whom we shall continue to support,''
Reagan said.
   `It will also be a major contribution to the improvement of
East-West relations,'' the president added.
   The United States had offered to cut off aid to the Afghan
rebels, but insisted that the Soviets stop supplying the Afghan
government. The Kremlin balked, saying it was obligated by treaty
to aid the Kabul regime.
   Offering a compromise, the United States suggested a policy of
``symmetry'' allowing the two sides to give assistance to rival
factions.
   Arriving in Las Vegas, Reagan was asked if a deal had been
struck on Afghanistan. ``We're very optimistic, but nothing's been
signed yet,'' he said.
   The president got a warm reception for his speech from the
audience of several thousand broadcasters.
   Reagan stopped in Las Vegas briefly before flying back to
Washington Sunday night after a 10-day vacation at his mountaintop
ranch near Santa Barbara, Calif.
   The speech was the first in a series of foreign policy addresses
Reagan will make before he visits Moscow May 29-June 2 for his
fourth summit meeting with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Reagan specifically said he will be talking about human rights
and regional conflicts in the coming weeks.
   Reagan said U.S. foreign policy toward the Soviet Union has
changed ``from containment _ the mere defense of our interests _ to
a strategy based upon the expansion of freedom.
   ``Nowhere has the world movement toward freedom and democracy
been more in evidence than in what might be called the outposts of
Soviet expansionism,'' Reagan said.
   ``For in Afghanistan, Cambodia, Africa, and, yes, Nicaragua, we
see domestic insurgencies directed against communist tyrants,''
Reagan said. ``And it has been a central part of our new strategy _
part of our new commitment to the expansion of freedom _ to help
them.''
   Referring to Nicaragua, Reagan said, ``It's no secret that I
believe Congress should have done more, much more, to aid the
freedom fighters.'' However, he said a humanitarian aid package
signed into law early this month ``will do much good.''
   Reagan also used the speech to comment on conditions in the
Soviet Union, saying it was a country that could not feed itself.
``And consider this, endless shortages and long lines force the
average Soviet family to spend two hours shopping every day just to
obtain the necessities of life.
   Reagan challenged Gorbachev to tear down a ``grim, invisible
wall of oppression'' that blocks the free flow of information and
ideas to Soviet-bloc nations.
   ``It is the wall that prevents the Communist world from joining
the West in this new age _ this dazzling new age _ of prosperity
and creativity,'' Reagan said.
   Specifically, he called on Gorbachev to open the Soviet Union to
Western newspapers and journals, permit Western broadcasts to go
unjammed and to permit access to all books.
   ``Here I have a specific first step to suggest,'' Reagan said.
``Mr. Gorbachev, open the Soviet Union to the works of a great man
and an historic author. Open the Soviet Union to the works of
(Alexander) Solzhenitsyn.''
   Solzhenitsyn, one of the Soviet Union's most famous dissidents
and writers, lives in exile in the United States.
</TEXT>
