<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CocaineBust     04-10 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cocaine Bust,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nearly 2,000 Pounds of Cocaine Seized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>McALLEN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customs agents Sunday seized nearly 2,000
pounds of cocaine and arrested the driver of a tractor-trailer rig
heading north from the Texas-Mexico border, authorities said.
   Agents removed 1,969 pounds of cocaine from the long-body
18-wheeler, Customs Service spokesman Charles Conroy said.
   The cocaine, with an estimated street value of more than $300
million, was hidden under a load of onions in the truck, said Mike
Cox of the Texas Department of Public Safety.
   DPS troopers and narcotics agents made the arrest with the
cooperation of federal agents, said Cox. The truck driver was
booked into the Brooks County jail in Falfurrias, he said, but
formal charges were not immediately filed.
   The seizure was part of an ongoing investigation, said Conroy,
adding more arrests were expected later in McAllen.
   Authorities seized 18,744 pounds of cocaine along the
U.S.-Mexican border in fiscal 1987, up from 3,975 in 1986,
according to Operation Alliance, a task force of local, state and
federal authorities in the Southwest border states.
</TEXT>
