<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-KingJr.     04-10 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-King Jr.,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Martin Luther King Musical Cheered In London</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new British musical about Dr. Martin Luther King
Jr. received a six-minute standing ovation Sunday night at a
concert performance honoring the assassinated civil rights leader.
   Producers hoped the charity preview would generate support for a
commercial engagement of the play.
   ``I feel numb,'' Martin Smith, the composer-librettist of
``King,'' said following the audience response to his musical in
its premiere at the Prince Edward Theater.
   The musical, which portrays the life of the Nobel Prize-winning
black minister, began 20 minutes late because of a bomb scare. But
it proceeded without incident, except for some minor technical
mishaps with video projections.
   Smith, a 30-year-old Scot who started work on ``King'' five
years ago, said of the reception, ``It was wonderful. You couldn't
ask for more.''
   More than 60 percent of the tickets were sold for the
performance at the 1,616-seat theater.
   Obba Babatunde, a New Yorker who won a 1982 Tony Award for
``Dreamgirls,'' received the lion's share of the cheers for his
portrayal of the Dr. King, who was assassinated April 4, 1968, in
Memphis, Tennessee.
   The 75 cast members and 24 musicians worked without pay for the
concert, which was expected to raise $18,700 for two charities: the
Terence Higgins trust, devoted to AIDS research in Britain, and the
Save the Children Fund.
   Although reference was made to King's most celebrated speeches,
his actual words were not spoken on-stage in accordance with
copyright laws.
   Smith said the King family had instead given its approval to a
second English musical on the slain leader, which is due to be
produced on New York's Broadway within the year.
</TEXT>
