<HEAD>Iranians To Defy Saudi Decree Limiting Mecca Pilgrimages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran will defy a Saudi Arabian decree
calling for a reduction in the number of Moslems attending the
annual pilgrimage to the holy city of Mecca, Iran's official news
agency reported Sunday.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency quoted Hojatoleslam Mahdi
Karrubi, head of Iran's pilgrim organization, as saying this year's
pilgrimage will be conducted ``more splendidly than last year.''
   More than 400 pilgrims, including 275 Iranians, were killed by
Saudi count in clashes between Iranian demonstrators and Saudi
police during last year's pilgrimage to Mecca, Islam's holiest city.
   The clashes erupted when the Iranians staged political rallies
in defiance of a Saudi ban.
   Iran will send some 150,000 pilgrims to Mecca this year,
according to the news agency. That is the same number as last year.
The peak of the pilgrimage period is in July.
   The Saudis, whose relations with Iran deteriorated after last
year's violence, have asked all Moslem countries to reduce the
number of pilgrims they send this year to prevent disorders.
   Iran has called for the ouster of the Saudi royal family as
guardians of Islam's holy shrines.
   Relations have been strained between Iran and Saudi Arabia since
Persian Iran and Arab Iraq went to war in September 1980.
</TEXT>
