<HEAD>Rain And Snow In The Ozarks; Record Heat In Northwest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to UPDATE with records in many Western cities. SUBS
6-7th grafs pvs, bgng `Casper, Wyo...', with 5 grafs to add detail.
Picks up 8th graf pvs, `Temperatures around...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cold rain fell Sunday over the Ozarks of southwestern Missouri
and northwestern Arkansas, mixed wth snow at times at some of the
higher elevations. But high-temperature records were set in parts
of the West.
   A half-inch of snow accumulated on grassy areas in the
Berryville and Eureka Springs areas of Arkansas but streets and
highways were just wet.
   Rain also fell from western Arkansas into southeastern Texas,
with a few showers in western Kansas.
   Elsewhere, showers were widely scattered in Florida, and a
thunderstorm developed over Gainesville during the afternoon.
   Chilly weather prevailed over the Plains with afternoon
temperatures in the 40s and 50s from North Dakota to south-central
Texas. Frost was expected overnight in parts of Kansas.
   Casper, Wyo., had a record low of 18 degrees, but record highs
were posted in a number of cities farther West.
   Seattle posted a temperature of 74 degrees, 5 degrees above the
record set in 1978. Astoria, Ore., had a record high of 68 Sunday,
and in Olympia, Wash., it hit 77 degrees, breaking the 1942 record
by 3 degrees. The temperature in Reno, Nev., was 82, beating the
1949 record by 1 degree.
   California was sweltering. The mercury climbed to 91 degrees in
San Francisco, the warmest temperature in the entire month of April
in the 113 years records have been kept. The old record for an
April 10, set in 1904, was 84 degrees.
   ``It's hot, but it doesn't mean the world is coming to an end.
It could be a cool summer,'' said Dave Williamson, a National
Weather Service forecaster in Redwood City. ``But it looks like the
month of April is going to be an unusually warm month.''
   Records for the date were also set in Sacramento, 93 degrees;
Santa Rosa, 88 degrees; San Jose, 91 degrees; Oakland, 88 degrees;
Alameda, 88 degrees; Bakersfield, 95; and Fresno, 91.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 36
degrees at Fayetteville, Ark., to 92 at El Cajon, Calif. The
early-morning low for the day was zero at Yellowstone National
Park, Wyo.
   For Monday, rain was forecast in the Mississippi Valley, the
Gulf Coast and southern Atlantic Coast states, with a few
thunderstorms from Mississippi across Alabama to Georgia and
Florida. Light rain and drizzle were forecast for eastern New
England.
   Highs only in the 30s were predicted in northern Maine; in the
40s or 50s from the rest of New England across the Great Lakes
region and the entire Mississippi Valley to eastern sections of the
Plains; near 80 in southern Florida; in the 80s and 90s from the
desert Southwest to southern and interior sections of California;
and in the 60s or 70s across most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
