<FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-88 1532EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SpecHouse Bjt   04-10 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spec House, Bjt,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$8.5 Million House Is Finished But Empty</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALT SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nothing burns in its 10 fireplaces, no glasses
clink at any of its five bars and its dog shower goes unoccupied.
   In fact, all 23,000 square feet of the newly completed, $8.5
million North Dallas mansion are empty and unused, except for an
occasional party designed to show the house off to prospective
buyers.
   The mansion on 1.5 acres in the prestigious Preston Hollow area
is believed to be the largest, most expensive ever built on
speculation in Dallas. It was completed last month but still does
not have an owner.
   But builder John Needham, who began the house more than two
years ago when the city's housing economy was near its peak, says
he believes there is a market for his seven-bedroom creation.
   ``There is an intense amount of interest in it. ... But it's
hard to say with a house of this magnitude,'' Needham said.
   The house does have magnitude.
   Needham was interviewed at a recent landscape lighting party
intended to highlight the five gardens around the mansion's
Olympic-size swimming pool and reflecting ponds.
   The largest of the seven bedrooms practically is a house in
itself: it's a two-level, 3,800 square-foot master suite with its
own small kitchen, his and hers bathrooms, a whirlpool, a sitting
area and dressing rooms. Upstairs is room for a desk plus several
sofas.
   The three-story building also includes a two-story library,
complete with a bar, reading rooms and a wine rack; a billiard room
and an exercise room, both accessible by elevator.
   Of course, the servants' quarters has its own staircase in back
so the help do not interrupt family suppers in the banquet hall or
a party centered around the grand saloon.
   The six-car garage has its own car wash so the chauffeur doesn't
have to wait in line at the car wash on a hot summer day.
   And then there's the ``doggy shower.'' It was included in the
large laundry room because there's never any place to wash the dog
in a house, explained Rona Victorson, the real estate agent
attempting to sell the mansion.
   Despite its price tag and size, Ms. Victorson and Needham say
the mansion is attracting prospective buyers.
   ``We've had people from out of town and Dallasites interested,''
Ms. Victorson said. ``I feel the large properties are now beginning
to sell.''
   When Needham began the house, the Dallas housing market was
riding a booming regional economy that was buoyed by sturdy oil
prices. Several large multimillion-dollar homes were sold before
they were completed, including the pink house down the street owned
by cosmetics magnate Mary Kay Ash.
   Although the subsequent oil slump hammered the real estate
market, Needham said the Dallas market is improving and at least
two other houses in a similar price range are being built.
   ``We feel very comfortable that the house is going to sell,''
Needham said. ``In light of today's market, we had to go ahead and
get it finished first. If the market had been better we could have
sold it with just the framing.''
   The house originally cost $7.5 million, but the price tag was
raised to $8.5 million after Needham decided to complete the house.
   Dr. Barbara Reagan, an economist at Southern Methodist
University, said a house that expensive would be more difficult to
sell, but not impossible in the improving area housing market.
   ``It's very location-specific, but it's perking up a little
bit,'' she said of the market. ``Some areas are holding up better
than others. We're kind of just bumping along.''
   Ms. Victorson said she never thought the Dallas housing market
was doing as poorly as some people perceived, but she acknowledged
interest in the house hasn't been as great as it might have been
several years ago.
   ``We've had certainly a sluggish economy,'' she said. ``But a
lot of the Dallas players that may have dropped out are back in
it.''
</TEXT>
