<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GasolinePrices     04-10 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gasoline Prices,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey: Gas Average Jumps 1.18 Cents Per Gallon, More Increases
Likely</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average retail price of gasoline rose by
more than a penny in the past two weeks, bringing the price even
with where it was a year ago, according to an industry survey
released Sunday.
   The price increase for all grades of gasoline was 1.18 cents a
gallon, pushing the average price to 96.14 cents a gallon in the
period ended April 8, according to the Lundberg Survey of gasoline
prices from stations around the United States.
   The increase followed a 0.78 cent a gallon decline in the
previous two-week period, but the average price was ``virtually the
exact same average price that Americans paid in April of 1987,''
analyst Trilby Lundberg said.
   According to the latest survey, prices per gallon at
self-service pumps were: regular unleaded, 86.80 cents; premium
unleaded, 101.84 cents; regular leaded, 83.97 cents.
   Prices at full-service pumps were: regular unleaded, 116.93
cents; premium unleaded, 127.20 cents; regular leaded, 112.51 cents.
   Although the previous period had seen a decline in the average,
which includes all grades, types of service and taxes, wholesale
price increases since then had prompted retailers to pass their
higher costs to consumers, Ms. Lundberg said.
</TEXT>
